PART 1 — Create S3 Bucket + Public Access
STEP 1 — Open S3

Go to:

AWS Console
Open Amazon S3
STEP 2 — Create Bucket

Click:

Create bucket

Fill:

Field	Value
Bucket Name	my-public-bucket-123
Region	nearest region

Bucket names must be globally unique.

Example:

my-public-bucket-jash-2026
STEP 3 — Disable Block Public Access

Scroll to:

Block Public Access settings

Uncheck:

Block all public access

Also uncheck all 4 options.

Tick:

I acknowledge...
Why?

By default S3 blocks public access for security.

STEP 4 — Create Bucket

Click:

Create bucket

Bucket created.

PART 2 — Enable Public Access
STEP 5 — Open Bucket

Click bucket name.

Go to:

Permissions
STEP 6 — Enable Bucket ACL Public Read

Scroll to:

Access Control List (ACL)

Click:

Edit

Under:

Everyone (public access)

Enable:

Read

Save changes.

PART 3 — Upload File
STEP 7 — Upload Object

Go to:

Objects

Click:

Upload

Then:

Add files

Select any file:

image.jpg

Click:

Upload
STEP 8 — Enable Public Access for Object

Click uploaded file.

Go to:

Permissions

Scroll:

ACL

Click:

Edit

Under:

Everyone (public access)

Enable:

Read

Save changes.

STEP 9 — Test Public URL

Open:

Object URL

Paste in browser.

If configured correctly:

file opens publicly
PART 4 — Enable Versioning
STEP 10 — Open Bucket Properties

Inside bucket:

Properties

Scroll:

Bucket Versioning

Click:

Edit

Select:

Enable

Save changes.

STEP 11 — Upload Same File Again

Upload:

report.pdf

again with same name.

What Happens?

S3:

keeps old version
creates new version

Nothing is overwritten permanently.

STEP 12 — View Versions

Go to:

Objects

Enable:

Show versions

You will see:

multiple versions
unique Version IDs
STEP 13 — Delete File

Delete:

report.pdf
What Happens?

S3 creates:

Delete Marker

Old versions still exist.

STEP 14 — Restore Deleted File

Remove delete marker.

The older file becomes visible again.

PART 5 — Cross Region Replication (CRR)
What CRR Does

Automatically copies files:

Source Bucket → Destination Bucket

Across different AWS regions.

STEP 15 — Create Destination Bucket

Create another bucket.

Example:

Setting	Value
Bucket Name	dest-crr-bucket
Region	Different region

Example:

Source → Mumbai
Destination → Singapore
STEP 16 — Enable Versioning on Destination Bucket

Repeat:

Properties → Bucket Versioning → Enable

CRR requires:

versioning ON for both buckets
STEP 17 — Configure Replication Rule

Open:

Source Bucket

Go:

Management

Open:

Replication Rules

Click:

Create replication rule
STEP 18 — Configure Rule

Fill:

Field	Value
Rule Name	academy-crr-rule
Status	Enabled
Scope	Apply to all objects
STEP 19 — Choose Destination Bucket

Select:

Another bucket

Choose destination bucket.

Use:

AWS Managed Role
STEP 20 — Save Rule

Click:

Save

Replication enabled.

STEP 21 — Test Replication

Upload file to source bucket:

image.png

Open destination bucket.

You should see:

image.png

automatically copied.

PART 6 — Static Website Hosting
STEP 22 — Create Website Files

Create:

index.html

Example:

<html>
<body>
<h1>Welcome to My Website</h1>
</body>
</html>

Create:

error.html

Example:

<html>
<body>
<h1>Error Page</h1>
</body>
</html>
STEP 23 — Upload Files

Upload:

index.html
error.html

to bucket.

STEP 24 — Enable Static Website Hosting

Go:

Properties

Scroll:

Static Website Hosting

Click:

Edit

Select:

Enable

Choose:

Host a static website

Fill:

Field	Value
Index Document	index.html
Error Document	error.html

Save.

STEP 25 — Make Bucket Public

Go:

Permissions

Enable:

ACL → Everyone → Read
STEP 26 — Make Objects Public

For BOTH:

index.html
error.html

Enable:

Everyone → Read
STEP 27 — Open Website

Go:

Properties

Scroll:

Static Website Hosting

Copy:

Bucket Website Endpoint

Open in browser.

Website loads.

STEP 28 — Test Error Page

Open:

/invalid.html

Example:

http://bucket-name.s3-website-region.amazonaws.com/abc.html

You should see:

error.html
